the personal care services industry. About 37% were self-employed”. Possibly because their job involves making others feel and look better, Estheticians report high levels of job satisfaction!\r\n<h2 class=\"cufon_headings\"><strong>Career Outlook</strong></h2>\r\nEsthetics employment is expected to grow 25% between 2010 and 2020, according to the US Labor Bureau, at a rate much faster than the average. Because of the aging population and cultural focus on staying healthy and looking good, Estheticians will continue to be in demand','Advanced Esthetics Training','','inherit','closed','closed','','202-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:14:03','2016-08-14 11:14:03','',202,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/202-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(204,1,'2016-08-14 11:17:12','2016-08-14 11:17:12','<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">ILLINOIS LICENSING REQUIREMENTS:</h3>\r\nEsthetician: 750 Hours\r\n\r\nEsthetics Teacher: 750 Hours or &gt;2 years of experience + 500 hours\r\n\r\nCosmetologist: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nBarber: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nNail Tech: 350 Hours\r\n\r\nMassage Therapist: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIllinois Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nBarber licenses and barber teacher licenses expire on July 31 of each odd-numbered year, and licensees may renew within the month prior to expiration. Cosmetology instructors, cosmetology clinic teachers and cosmetology licenses expire on September 30 of each even-numbered year. Illinois requires cosmetologists to certify on their renewal applications that they have successfully completed 14 hours of cosmetology continuing education within the 2-year licensure period. Cosmetology instructors and cosmetology clinic teachers must show a minimum of 24 hours of continuing education from a sponsor registered with the division within the 2-year licensure period.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) to Illinois\r\n\r\nTo transfer your license to Illinois, you’ll need to show an official certification of licensure from the board of your home state where you’re currently licensed and practicing. If it’s not the original copy of your license it must include: legal name, cosmetologist license number, original issuance date, expiration date, brief description of any licensing exams taken and the grades received, and whether you have any disciplinary actions taken or pending against your license.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIL State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nIllinois Dept. of Professional Regulation\r\n\r\n320W. Washington St., 3rd Fl.\r\n\r\nSpringfield, IL 62786\r\n\r\n100 W. Randolph Street, 9th Fl.\r\n\r\nChicago, IL 60601\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 217-782-8556\r\n\r\nFax Number: 217-782-7645\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Illinois State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Illinois state cosmetology license.\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\"></h1>\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\">Missouri</h1>\r\n<strong>Missouri Board of Cosmetology License Requirements</strong>\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1500 Hours (3000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 1000 Hours (2000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 750 Hours (1500 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (800 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nPERMANENT MAKEUP LICENSE: 300 Hours Apprenticeship\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 600 Hours\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMissouri Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology license renewal in Missouri happens biennially (every 2 years). Cosmetology licenses expire on September 30 in the odd-numbered years. The cost to renew beauty licenses in Missouri is $30.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Missouri\r\n\r\nCosmetology license transfer depends on your home state and how comparable their training hours are to Missouri’s. Missouri requires NIC testing for all transfers. Though cosmetology continuing education is only required for instructors, cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMO State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nMissouri Board of Cosmetology and Barber Examiners\r\n\r\n3605 Missouri Boulevard, PO Box 1062\r\n\r\nJefferson City, MO 65102-1062\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 866-762-9432\r\n\r\nFax Number: 573-751-8167\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: cosbar@pr.mo.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Kentucky Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nLast Updated: September 26, 2012\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Kentucky, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Kentucky State Board of Cosmetology. When getting a Kentucky cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Kentucky’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Kentucky State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Kentucky cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Kentucky. Keep in mind, even though Kentucky may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Kentucky annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the KY Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of KY does allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. KY offers the cosmetology board exams in English only.\r\n\r\nFind Kentucky beauty schools that can help you obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics, nail technology and other beauty professions in the State of Kentucky.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1800 Hours\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 1000 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: 1000 Hours + Cosmetology License\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology licenses in Kentucky must be renewed every year between July 1 and July 31. The average cost of cosmetology license renewals is $20. Currently, no continuing education hours are required to renew your cosmetology license in Kentucky, but CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Kentucky\r\n\r\nKentucky currently does not have cosmetology license reciprocity. Any applicant from out-of-state who must have their board send the proper state certificate, and then the applicant can print out the application online and submit it. You may be required to take the Kentucky written or practical board exams. Applicants must pay the out-of-state examination fee and the license fee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKY State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nKentucky Board of Hairdressers and Cosmetologists\r\n\r\n111 St. James Court, Suite A\r\n\r\nFrankfort, Kentucky 40601\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 502-564-4262\r\n\r\nFax Number: 502-564-0481\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWisconsin Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1800 Hours (4000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: Coming Soon\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 450 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 300 Hours (300 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nPERMANENT MAKEUP ARTIST LICENSE: Contact Department of Health Tattooing Dept.\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: 450 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: License + 150 Hours + 2000 Hours Work Experience\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWisconsin Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology license renewal in Wisconsin happens every 2 years in March of odd-numbered years. The cost is $82 to renew licenses, or an additional $25 if the license is renewed late. Currently WI does not require cosmetology continuing education hours to renew licenses, however that may change in the 2015 renewal cycle. Cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Wisconsin\r\n\r\nTo transfer your license to Wisconsin, you must have 4000 hours of licensed experience and go through the WI license transfer application process. If you do not yet have 4000 hours of work experience, you will need to take the WI board exams.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWI State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nWisconsin Barbering &amp; Cosmetology Examining Board\r\n\r\nPO Box 8935\r\n\r\n1400 E. Washington Ave.\r\n\r\nMadison WI 53703\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 608-266-5511\r\n\r\nFax Number: 608-261-7083\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: DSPS@wisconsin.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Wisconsin State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining a Wisconsin state cosmetology license.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\">Indiana Board of Cosmetology License Requirements</h1>\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE INFORMATION</h3>\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Indiana, students must complete the requirements listed below from the <strong>Indiana State Board of Cosmetology</strong>. When getting an Indiana cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Indiana’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Indiana State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Indiana cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Indiana. Keep in mind, even though Indiana may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Indiana annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the IN Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of IN does not allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. IN uses Pearson Vue for its cosmetology board exams, and you may take the exam in English, Spanish, Vietnamese or Simplified Chinese for cosmetology, nail tech and esthetics. You can take the barber license and cosmetology instructor exams in English or Spanish. The electrology license exam is offered only in English.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>C</strong><strong>OSMETOLOGIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 1500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>BARBER</strong><strong> LICENSE: 1500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>ESTHETICIAN</strong><strong> LICENSE: 700 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>NAIL TECHNICIAN</strong><strong> LICENSE: 450 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>ELECTROLOGIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 300 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>COSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR</strong><strong> LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 1000 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>MASSAGE THERAPIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA COSMETOLOGY LICENSE RENEWAL</h3>\r\nIndiana cosmetology licenses expire on August 1 every 4 years. Barber licenses expire on September 1 every 4 years. If your license has been expired more than 3 years, you must re-take the practical exam to get re-licensed. The cost to renew cosmetology licenses in Indiana is $40, but if you are late there is an additional $50 penalty. You can renew your license up to 60 days prior to its expiration, and 24 to 48 hours later can print a free license card, or you can order a blue card online for $13.75. Indiana does not currently require additional cosmetology continuing education hours to renew.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">COSMETOLOGY LICENSE RECIPROCITY (TRANSFER) TO INDIANA</h3>\r\nReciprocity is granted in Indiana on a case-by-case basis depending on whether your home state has similar or equivalent education and licensing requirements. You may not transfer if you have only attended nail school but have not worked actively with the license, and you may be required to take additional training. However for cosmetology it is acceptable to transfer a license with school hours only. Electrologists must have cosmetology or esthetician licenses to transfer. There is a $40 fee and an application to transfer your license to Indiana. If your license does not meet the same standards that Indiana requires, you can instead have a minimum of 1000 hours of training plus 5 years of work history. You would need to provide a work affidavit form showing that you’ve worked in the field for a minimum of 5 years (500 hours per year). Manicurists must show a minimum of 300 training hours and 1 1/2 years work experience to transfer. Estheticians must show 400 training hours and 3 years work experience to transfer. Electrologists must show 200 training hours and 1 year work experience to transfer. Cosmetology instructors must show 700 training hours and 3 years work experience to transfer.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">IN STATE BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY CONTACT INFORMATION</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Indiana Board of Cosmetology\" href=\"http://www.pla.in.gov/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Indiana Professional Licensing Agency</a>\r\nState Board of Cosmetology Examiners\r\n402 W. Washington St., Rm. W0-72\r\nIndianapolis, IN 46204\r\nPhone Number: 317-234-3031\r\nFax Number: 317-233-4236\r\nE-mail Address: <a href=\"mailto:pla12@pla.in.gov\">pla12@pla.in.gov</a>\r\n\r\nThe Indiana State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating a change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Indiana cosmetology license.\r\n\r\nPrevious Next\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Iowa, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Iowa State Board of Cosmetology. When getting an Iowa cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Iowa’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Iowa State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Iowa cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Iowa. Keep in mind, even though Iowa only requires 8 hours of continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Iowa annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the IA Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of IA does allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. IA uses PSI for its cosmetology board exams, and you may take the exam in English only.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">IOWA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 2100 Hours\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: Coming Soon – Barbering Board Handles This\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 325 Hours\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: 400 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 1000 Hours Instructor Training OR 2 Years Work Experience in Last 6 Years\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa cosmetology licenses expire every two years, and must be renewed by December 31 of even-numbered years. The fee to renew your license is $60. Iowa requires 8 hours of cosmetology continuing education each period to renew.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) to Iowa</strong>\r\n\r\nIowa does not have reciprocity arrangements with other states. You may gain licensure through endorsement instead. Each application for transfer is reviewed on a case-by-case basis. Your home state must have similar or equivalent licensing requirements. Depending on the length of your licensure and the exam you took in your home state, you may be required to take the Iowa exams or get additional training hours.\r\n\r\nIA State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology Arts &amp; Sciences\r\n\r\nLucas Bldg., 5th Floor, 321 E. 12th Street\r\n\r\nDes Moines, IA 50319-0075\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 515-281-4416\r\n\r\nFax Number: 515-281-3121\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: rosemary.bonanno@idph.iowa.gov\r\n\r\nThe Iowa State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Iowa state cosmetology license.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">MICHIGAN STATE BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\nMichigan Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Michigan, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Michigan State Board of Cosmetology. When getting a Michigan cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Michigan’s minimum required training hours. The state does allow apprenticeship to get training hours for some licenses. Then you must take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Michigan State Board of Cosmetology. Michigan uses PSI to administer the exam, which can be taken in the English language only (though a word-to-word language dictionary may be used) on the first attempt, though they may allow translators on the second attempt. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Michigan cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Michigan. Keep in mind, even though Michigan may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Michigan annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the MI Board of Cosmetology directly for more information.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFind Michigan beauty schools that can help you obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics, nail technology, and other programs in the State of Michigan.\r\n\r\nMichigan Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1500 Hours (2-Year Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 2000 Hours\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: C400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 500 Hours\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYour first year of licensure is until the upcoming August. After that, cosmetology licenses in Michigan must be renewed every two years in by the end of August. No continuing education hours are required to renew your license in Michigan, but cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry. The cost to renew is $48.\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Michigan\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan grants cosmetology license reciprocity or transfer if the training and testing requirements in your home state are substantially equal to Michigan’s. If they are not similar or greater, you may be required to take additional training hours or to take the Michigan written and practical board exams. The cost to transfer your cosmetology license to MI is $39.\r\n\r\nMI State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan Bureau of Commercial Services – Board of Cosmetology\r\n\r\nPO Box 30018\r\n\r\nLansing, MI 48909\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 517-241-8720\r\n\r\nFax Number: 517-373-1044\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: bcslic@michigan.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Michigan State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Michigan state cosmetology license.','Licensing','','publish','closed','closed','','licensing','','','2016-08-14 11:17:12','2016-08-14 11:17:12','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?page_id=204',0,'page','',0),(205,1,'2016-08-14 11:17:12','2016-08-14 11:17:12','<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">ILLINOIS LICENSING REQUIREMENTS:</h3>\r\nEsthetician: 750 Hours\r\n\r\nEsthetics Teacher: 750 Hours or &gt;2 years of experience + 500 hours\r\n\r\nCosmetologist: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nBarber: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nNail Tech: 350 Hours\r\n\r\nMassage Therapist: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIllinois Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nBarber licenses and barber teacher licenses expire on July 31 of each odd-numbered year, and licensees may renew within the month prior to expiration. Cosmetology instructors, cosmetology clinic teachers and cosmetology licenses expire on September 30 of each even-numbered year. Illinois requires cosmetologists to certify on their renewal applications that they have successfully completed 14 hours of cosmetology continuing education within the 2-year licensure period. Cosmetology instructors and cosmetology clinic teachers must show a minimum of 24 hours of continuing education from a sponsor registered with the division within the 2-year licensure period.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) to Illinois\r\n\r\nTo transfer your license to Illinois, you’ll need to show an official certification of licensure from the board of your home state where you’re currently licensed and practicing. If it’s not the original copy of your license it must include: legal name, cosmetologist license number, original issuance date, expiration date, brief description of any licensing exams taken and the grades received, and whether you have any disciplinary actions taken or pending against your license.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIL State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nIllinois Dept. of Professional Regulation\r\n\r\n320W. Washington St., 3rd Fl.\r\n\r\nSpringfield, IL 62786\r\n\r\n100 W. Randolph Street, 9th Fl.\r\n\r\nChicago, IL 60601\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 217-782-8556\r\n\r\nFax Number: 217-782-7645\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Illinois State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Illinois state cosmetology license.\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\"></h1>\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\">Missouri</h1>\r\n<strong>Missouri Board of Cosmetology License Requirements</strong>\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1500 Hours (3000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 1000 Hours (2000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 750 Hours (1500 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (800 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nPERMANENT MAKEUP LICENSE: 300 Hours Apprenticeship\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 600 Hours\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMissouri Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology license renewal in Missouri happens biennially (every 2 years). Cosmetology licenses expire on September 30 in the odd-numbered years. The cost to renew beauty licenses in Missouri is $30.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Missouri\r\n\r\nCosmetology license transfer depends on your home state and how comparable their training hours are to Missouri’s. Missouri requires NIC testing for all transfers. Though cosmetology continuing education is only required for instructors, cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMO State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nMissouri Board of Cosmetology and Barber Examiners\r\n\r\n3605 Missouri Boulevard, PO Box 1062\r\n\r\nJefferson City, MO 65102-1062\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 866-762-9432\r\n\r\nFax Number: 573-751-8167\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: cosbar@pr.mo.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Kentucky Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nLast Updated: September 26, 2012\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Kentucky, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Kentucky State Board of Cosmetology. When getting a Kentucky cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Kentucky’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Kentucky State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Kentucky cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Kentucky. Keep in mind, even though Kentucky may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Kentucky annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the KY Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of KY does allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. KY offers the cosmetology board exams in English only.\r\n\r\nFind Kentucky beauty schools that can help you obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics, nail technology and other beauty professions in the State of Kentucky.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1800 Hours\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 1500 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 1000 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: 1000 Hours + Cosmetology License\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKentucky Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology licenses in Kentucky must be renewed every year between July 1 and July 31. The average cost of cosmetology license renewals is $20. Currently, no continuing education hours are required to renew your cosmetology license in Kentucky, but CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Kentucky\r\n\r\nKentucky currently does not have cosmetology license reciprocity. Any applicant from out-of-state who must have their board send the proper state certificate, and then the applicant can print out the application online and submit it. You may be required to take the Kentucky written or practical board exams. Applicants must pay the out-of-state examination fee and the license fee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKY State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nKentucky Board of Hairdressers and Cosmetologists\r\n\r\n111 St. James Court, Suite A\r\n\r\nFrankfort, Kentucky 40601\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 502-564-4262\r\n\r\nFax Number: 502-564-0481\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWisconsin Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1800 Hours (4000 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: Coming Soon\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 450 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 300 Hours (300 Hours Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nPERMANENT MAKEUP ARTIST LICENSE: Contact Department of Health Tattooing Dept.\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: 450 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: License + 150 Hours + 2000 Hours Work Experience\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWisconsin Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\nCosmetology license renewal in Wisconsin happens every 2 years in March of odd-numbered years. The cost is $82 to renew licenses, or an additional $25 if the license is renewed late. Currently WI does not require cosmetology continuing education hours to renew licenses, however that may change in the 2015 renewal cycle. Cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Wisconsin\r\n\r\nTo transfer your license to Wisconsin, you must have 4000 hours of licensed experience and go through the WI license transfer application process. If you do not yet have 4000 hours of work experience, you will need to take the WI board exams.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWI State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\nWisconsin Barbering &amp; Cosmetology Examining Board\r\n\r\nPO Box 8935\r\n\r\n1400 E. Washington Ave.\r\n\r\nMadison WI 53703\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 608-266-5511\r\n\r\nFax Number: 608-261-7083\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: DSPS@wisconsin.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Wisconsin State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining a Wisconsin state cosmetology license.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1 class=\"cufon_headings\">Indiana Board of Cosmetology License Requirements</h1>\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE INFORMATION</h3>\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Indiana, students must complete the requirements listed below from the <strong>Indiana State Board of Cosmetology</strong>. When getting an Indiana cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Indiana’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Indiana State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Indiana cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Indiana. Keep in mind, even though Indiana may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Indiana annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the IN Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of IN does not allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. IN uses Pearson Vue for its cosmetology board exams, and you may take the exam in English, Spanish, Vietnamese or Simplified Chinese for cosmetology, nail tech and esthetics. You can take the barber license and cosmetology instructor exams in English or Spanish. The electrology license exam is offered only in English.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>C</strong><strong>OSMETOLOGIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 1500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>BARBER</strong><strong> LICENSE: 1500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>ESTHETICIAN</strong><strong> LICENSE: 700 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>NAIL TECHNICIAN</strong><strong> LICENSE: 450 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>ELECTROLOGIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 300 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>COSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR</strong><strong> LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 1000 Hours</strong></li>\r\n 	<li><strong>MASSAGE THERAPIST</strong><strong> LICENSE: 500 Hours</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">INDIANA COSMETOLOGY LICENSE RENEWAL</h3>\r\nIndiana cosmetology licenses expire on August 1 every 4 years. Barber licenses expire on September 1 every 4 years. If your license has been expired more than 3 years, you must re-take the practical exam to get re-licensed. The cost to renew cosmetology licenses in Indiana is $40, but if you are late there is an additional $50 penalty. You can renew your license up to 60 days prior to its expiration, and 24 to 48 hours later can print a free license card, or you can order a blue card online for $13.75. Indiana does not currently require additional cosmetology continuing education hours to renew.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">COSMETOLOGY LICENSE RECIPROCITY (TRANSFER) TO INDIANA</h3>\r\nReciprocity is granted in Indiana on a case-by-case basis depending on whether your home state has similar or equivalent education and licensing requirements. You may not transfer if you have only attended nail school but have not worked actively with the license, and you may be required to take additional training. However for cosmetology it is acceptable to transfer a license with school hours only. Electrologists must have cosmetology or esthetician licenses to transfer. There is a $40 fee and an application to transfer your license to Indiana. If your license does not meet the same standards that Indiana requires, you can instead have a minimum of 1000 hours of training plus 5 years of work history. You would need to provide a work affidavit form showing that you’ve worked in the field for a minimum of 5 years (500 hours per year). Manicurists must show a minimum of 300 training hours and 1 1/2 years work experience to transfer. Estheticians must show 400 training hours and 3 years work experience to transfer. Electrologists must show 200 training hours and 1 year work experience to transfer. Cosmetology instructors must show 700 training hours and 3 years work experience to transfer.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">IN STATE BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY CONTACT INFORMATION</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Indiana Board of Cosmetology\" href=\"http://www.pla.in.gov/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Indiana Professional Licensing Agency</a>\r\nState Board of Cosmetology Examiners\r\n402 W. Washington St., Rm. W0-72\r\nIndianapolis, IN 46204\r\nPhone Number: 317-234-3031\r\nFax Number: 317-233-4236\r\nE-mail Address: <a href=\"mailto:pla12@pla.in.gov\">pla12@pla.in.gov</a>\r\n\r\nThe Indiana State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating a change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Indiana cosmetology license.\r\n\r\nPrevious Next\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Iowa, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Iowa State Board of Cosmetology. When getting an Iowa cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Iowa’s minimum required training hours and then take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Iowa State Board of Cosmetology. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Iowa cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Iowa. Keep in mind, even though Iowa only requires 8 hours of continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Iowa annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the IA Board of Cosmetology directly for more information. The state of IA does allow apprenticeship to get your training hours for some of the beauty profession licenses, see below. IA uses PSI for its cosmetology board exams, and you may take the exam in English only.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">IOWA BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 2100 Hours\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: Coming Soon – Barbering Board Handles This\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 600 Hours\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 325 Hours\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: 400 Hours\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 1000 Hours Instructor Training OR 2 Years Work Experience in Last 6 Years\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa cosmetology licenses expire every two years, and must be renewed by December 31 of even-numbered years. The fee to renew your license is $60. Iowa requires 8 hours of cosmetology continuing education each period to renew.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) to Iowa</strong>\r\n\r\nIowa does not have reciprocity arrangements with other states. You may gain licensure through endorsement instead. Each application for transfer is reviewed on a case-by-case basis. Your home state must have similar or equivalent licensing requirements. Depending on the length of your licensure and the exam you took in your home state, you may be required to take the Iowa exams or get additional training hours.\r\n\r\nIA State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIowa Board of Cosmetology Arts &amp; Sciences\r\n\r\nLucas Bldg., 5th Floor, 321 E. 12th Street\r\n\r\nDes Moines, IA 50319-0075\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 515-281-4416\r\n\r\nFax Number: 515-281-3121\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: rosemary.bonanno@idph.iowa.gov\r\n\r\nThe Iowa State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Iowa state cosmetology license.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\">MICHIGAN STATE BOARD OF COSMETOLOGY LICENSE REQUIREMENTS</h3>\r\nMichigan Board of Cosmetology License Information\r\n\r\nIn order to obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics or nail technology in the state of Michigan, students must complete the requirements listed below from the Michigan State Board of Cosmetology. When getting a Michigan cosmetology license or other beauty practitioner certification, you must attend a licensed school and complete the state of Michigan’s minimum required training hours. The state does allow apprenticeship to get training hours for some licenses. Then you must take the state’s cosmetology board exams. After finishing your training, you are required to pass a licensing exam issued by the Michigan State Board of Cosmetology. Michigan uses PSI to administer the exam, which can be taken in the English language only (though a word-to-word language dictionary may be used) on the first attempt, though they may allow translators on the second attempt. Once you pass this exam, you will receive your Michigan cosmetology license shortly thereafter. You’re now able to work in the state of Michigan. Keep in mind, even though Michigan may not require continuing education to renew some licenses, you may wish to consider taking cosmetology continuing education hours in Michigan annually to stay current on the latest trends. For specific questions, please contact the MI Board of Cosmetology directly for more information.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFind Michigan beauty schools that can help you obtain a license in cosmetology, esthetics, nail technology, and other programs in the State of Michigan.\r\n\r\nMichigan Board of Cosmetology License Requirements\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGIST LICENSE: 1500 Hours (2-Year Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nESTHETICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nNAIL TECHNICIAN LICENSE: 400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nBARBER LICENSE: 2000 Hours\r\n\r\nELECTROLOGIST LICENSE: C400 Hours (6-Month Apprenticeship)\r\n\r\nCOSMETOLOGY INSTRUCTOR LICENSE: Cosmetology License + 500 Hours\r\n\r\nMASSAGE THERAPIST LICENSE: 500 Hours\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan Cosmetology License Renewal\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYour first year of licensure is until the upcoming August. After that, cosmetology licenses in Michigan must be renewed every two years in by the end of August. No continuing education hours are required to renew your license in Michigan, but cosmetology CEUs are always recommended to stay current in the industry. The cost to renew is $48.\r\n\r\nCosmetology License Reciprocity (Transfer) in Michigan\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan grants cosmetology license reciprocity or transfer if the training and testing requirements in your home state are substantially equal to Michigan’s. If they are not similar or greater, you may be required to take additional training hours or to take the Michigan written and practical board exams. The cost to transfer your cosmetology license to MI is $39.\r\n\r\nMI State Board of Cosmetology Contact Information\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMichigan Bureau of Commercial Services – Board of Cosmetology\r\n\r\nPO Box 30018\r\n\r\nLansing, MI 48909\r\n\r\nPhone Number: 517-241-8720\r\n\r\nFax Number: 517-373-1044\r\n\r\nE-mail Address: bcslic@michigan.gov\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Michigan State Board of Cosmetology can help you with replacing a lost cosmetology license, updating change of name or change of address information, and acquiring out-of-state and other useful forms, as well as answer additional questions about obtaining an Michigan state cosmetology license.','Licensing','','inherit','closed','closed','','204-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:17:12','2016-08-14 11:17:12','',204,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/204-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(206,1,'2016-08-14 11:19:11','2016-08-14 11:19:11','','Calendar','','publish','closed','closed','','calendar','','','2016-08-14 11:19:11','2016-08-14 11:19:11','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?page_id=206',0,'page','',0),(207,1,'2016-08-14 11:19:11','2016-08-14 11:19:11','','Calendar','','inherit','closed','closed','','206-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:19:11','2016-08-14 11:19:11','',206,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/206-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(208,1,'2016-08-14 11:20:38','2016-08-14 11:20:38','Upon successfully finishing their studies, students are strongly encouraged to complete at least 160 hours at a medical site. The externship (also referred to as “internship”) is optional for the recipients of the G.I. Bill benefits. Students who have not completed an externship or obtained an equivalent professional experience will not be able to register for the NCCT certification.\r\n\r\nBecause of the quality of its training, ITA has an agreement with a leading teaching Chicago-land hospital. Students, who successfully complete all four modules of the MA program, are eligible to apply to complete a prestigious externship at the Dermatology Department of the Hospital. ITA also provides assistants for students who want to conduct an externship in private medical practices.','Externship','','publish','closed','closed','','externship','','','2016-08-14 11:20:38','2016-08-14 11:20:38','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?page_id=208',0,'page','',0),(209,1,'2016-08-14 11:20:38','2016-08-14 11:20:38','Upon successfully finishing their studies, students are strongly encouraged to complete at least 160 hours at a medical site. The externship (also referred to as “internship”) is optional for the recipients of the G.I. Bill benefits. Students who have not completed an externship or obtained an equivalent professional experience will not be able to register for the NCCT certification.\r\n\r\nBecause of the quality of its training, ITA has an agreement with a leading teaching Chicago-land hospital. Students, who successfully complete all four modules of the MA program, are eligible to apply to complete a prestigious externship at the Dermatology Department of the Hospital. ITA also provides assistants for students who want to conduct an externship in private medical practices.','Externship','','inherit','closed','closed','','208-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:20:38','2016-08-14 11:20:38','',208,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/208-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(210,1,'2016-08-14 11:21:12','2016-08-14 11:21:12','Because we are committed to giving our students the best education and employment opportunities, we have been approved by not one but two National agencies – National Healthcare Association <strong>(NHA) </strong>and National Center for Competency <strong>(NCCT)</strong>. Upon successful completion of the Medical Assistant Program, graduates receive a diploma and are eligible and to sign up for the exams and receive <strong>National Certifications</strong>. NHA examination and preparation are included in the cost of the program.','National Certification','','publish','closed','closed','','national-certification','','','2016-08-14 11:21:12','2016-08-14 11:21:12','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?page_id=210',0,'page','',0),(211,1,'2016-08-14 11:21:12','2016-08-14 11:21:12','Because we are committed to giving our students the best education and employment opportunities, we have been approved by not one but two National agencies – National Healthcare Association <strong>(NHA) </strong>and National Center for Competency <strong>(NCCT)</strong>. Upon successful completion of the Medical Assistant Program, graduates receive a diploma and are eligible and to sign up for the exams and receive <strong>National Certifications</strong>. NHA examination and preparation are included in the cost of the program.','National Certification','','inherit','closed','closed','','210-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:21:12','2016-08-14 11:21:12','',210,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/210-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(212,1,'2016-08-14 11:21:42','2016-08-14 11:21:42','<h2 class=\"cufon_headings\">Career in Medical Assisting</h2>\r\nMedical Assistant (MA) plays a vital role in the operation of a hospital or physician’s office. She performs minor clinical and administrative duties that make a medical facility run smoothly and successfully, ensuring the best treatment experience for both doctor and patient.\r\n\r\nThe tasks vary by office and specialty area. In smaller offices, Medical Assistants are usually generalists, providing both administrative and clinical support. In larger practices, Medical Assistants often specialize in certain areas.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\"><em>ADMINISTRATIVE DUTIES</em></h3>\r\nLike other medical administrative roles, MAs handle medical records and insurance information, arrange for hospital admissions and lab work, and manage office communications. Other office duties may include greeting patients, setting appointments and handling bookkeeping and billing.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\"><em>CLINICAL DUTIES</em></h3>\r\nClinical duties may include asepsis and infection control, taking patient histories and vital signs, performing first aid and CPR, preparing patients for procedures, performing electrocardiograms, assisting the physician with examinations and treatments, performing suture removal, collecting and processing specimens, performing selected lab and diagnostic tests, administering medications (injections), and drawing blood (Venipuncture).\r\n\r\n<strong>Career Outlook</strong>\r\n\r\nMedical Assistant employment is expected to grow 35% between 2006 and 2016, according to the US Labor Bureau. This growth is due to technological advancements in the medical field, as well as a growing population of elderly, which is dramatically increasing the demand for medical procedures.\r\n\r\nThe number of clinics operating in the US is also growing rapidly, creating need for formally trained assistants who can handle clinical and administrative duties.','CMA Career Opportunities','','publish','closed','closed','','cma-career-opportunities','','','2016-08-14 11:21:42','2016-08-14 11:21:42','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?page_id=212',0,'page','',0),(213,1,'2016-08-14 11:21:42','2016-08-14 11:21:42','<h2 class=\"cufon_headings\">Career in Medical Assisting</h2>\r\nMedical Assistant (MA) plays a vital role in the operation of a hospital or physician’s office. She performs minor clinical and administrative duties that make a medical facility run smoothly and successfully, ensuring the best treatment experience for both doctor and patient.\r\n\r\nThe tasks vary by office and specialty area. In smaller offices, Medical Assistants are usually generalists, providing both administrative and clinical support. In larger practices, Medical Assistants often specialize in certain areas.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\"><em>ADMINISTRATIVE DUTIES</em></h3>\r\nLike other medical administrative roles, MAs handle medical records and insurance information, arrange for hospital admissions and lab work, and manage office communications. Other office duties may include greeting patients, setting appointments and handling bookkeeping and billing.\r\n<h3 class=\"cufon_headings\"><em>CLINICAL DUTIES</em></h3>\r\nClinical duties may include asepsis and infection control, taking patient histories and vital signs, performing first aid and CPR, preparing patients for procedures, performing electrocardiograms, assisting the physician with examinations and treatments, performing suture removal, collecting and processing specimens, performing selected lab and diagnostic tests, administering medications (injections), and drawing blood (Venipuncture).\r\n\r\n<strong>Career Outlook</strong>\r\n\r\nMedical Assistant employment is expected to grow 35% between 2006 and 2016, according to the US Labor Bureau. This growth is due to technological advancements in the medical field, as well as a growing population of elderly, which is dramatically increasing the demand for medical procedures.\r\n\r\nThe number of clinics operating in the US is also growing rapidly, creating need for formally trained assistants who can handle clinical and administrative duties.','CMA Career Opportunities','','inherit','closed','closed','','212-revision-v1','','','2016-08-14 11:21:42','2016-08-14 11:21:42','',212,'http://design-austin.com/ita/2016/08/14/212-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(214,1,'2016-08-21 10:40:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2016-08-21 10:40:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://design-austin.com/ita/?p=214',0,'post','',0),(215,1,'2016-08-21 10:41:15','2016-08-21 10:41:15','<p class=\"p1\">We are leaded by doctor of Dermatology</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We built up a reputation of the best vocational school in IL</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We are Elite school called “Harvard of Skin care” by Spa owners</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We offer the most advanced and updated Clinical Esthetics and MA programs</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We teach unique techniques and will make you the best in your profession</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">We believe t