r to being a SAHM, I spent 12 years as a pharmaceuticals account rep and an office technology account executive, respectively.  I have been wanting to get my esthetics license for quite some time and this Fall, with both kids in school, I felt it was the right time to start.\n\nMaking the decision to be become an esthetician was the easy part in starting this new career path.  Finding a school that fit my needs was the hard part.  I was surprised when my esthetician told me to just find any school because she said most have you reading all the time and give you very little hands on experience.  In fact she didn\'t really learn to wax until her first job.  This is not what I wanted.  I knew there had to be a school out there that really did want their students to walk out ready and qualified to work.  I did a ton of research on schools in my area and then did my own homework by visiting several schools.  For me, everything had to fall in to place and fit with my needs and wants which were:\n<ul>\n	<li>Strong industry reputation.</li>\n	<li>Syllabus that offers both a good amount of theory (classroom learning) as well as a an <i>equal or more</i> amount of practical experience.</li>\n	<li>A high average percentage rate on state boards which means the school knows how to teach.</li>\n	<li>Full time day option</li>\n	<li>Close proximity to home to allow for pick up of my kids from school.</li>\n	<li>Smaller class size</li>\n</ul>\nIt was just when I had about given up and was thinking of postponing a year that I found International Skin Beauty Academy.  Upon visiting I knew immediately that it was the right fit.  I was impressed and super excited.  Dr. Doran couldn\'t be any more encouraging and lovely and her staff are professionals.  The high passing scores and amazing talent they produce are a testament to their teaching.  I have now experienced it first hand and can tell you that I made the right decision.  A wake everyday feeling blessed that I found this school.  A typical week for me is two days of theory and 3 days of practical.  We are learning facials, peels, extractions, all types of waxing and more.  Though certainly not easy, it has already been an amazing journey!\n\nMy blogs will follow my journey at International Skin Beauty Academy as an esthetics student and everything beauty and skin related, inside and out!','Happy Beginnings - a Student\'s Journey','','publish','open','open','','happy-beginnings-a-students-journey','','','2013-11-22 11:40:45','2013-11-22 17:40:45','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=298',0,'post','',0),(315,2,'2013-12-12 10:45:14','2013-12-12 16:45:14','<em><strong>Here\'a another post from our student Karen:</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"line-height:1.5em;\">One of the most interesting things I have learned in our esthetics program so far is just how amazing our skin is and what it does for us on a daily basis.   Skin is the largest organ in the body and also, in my opinion, the most complex <a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/itaskinbeauty-com-blog.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-316\" alt=\"intlacademy.wordpress.com\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/itaskinbeauty-com-blog.jpg\" width=\"195\" height=\"278\" /></a>and overlooked.  I think we are all guilty of neglecting our skin from time to time and really only taking care of it when there is a problem, for example after a sunburn, after you wake and realize you have a pimple, or when it is red and irritated, etc.</span>\n\nBut our skin plays a big role in our overall well-being and I thought it would be good to highlight everything our skin does for our bodies and show just how important it is to take care of our skin each and every day.\n\nThe following are the functions of the skin we learned in class and gave me a better understanding of just how important our skin is to our health. <b> </b>\n\n<b>Our Skin is for:</b>\n\n<b>Protection</b>\n\nUnbroken skin is a protective barrier protecting us from disease and infection.  To prevent irritation and water-loss, the skin\'s has a natural, built-in, barrier function.  Simply put, the barrier function helps moisturize our skin and keep irritants out.  It is made up of sebum, sweat, oil and water. Removing it is not good!  When all the oil from your skin is gone, guess what happens?  Your skin makes more oil to compensate for not having any to protect itself!   Daily stripping of oil can lead to chronic clogged pores in addition to irritation, sensitivity and dehydration.  It\'s a vicious cycle.  What I have learned is that part of a good daily skin care routine includes keeping your skin <i>balanced</i> so as to <i>reduce or eliminate</i> skin irritation, sensitivity and dehydration as well as protect it from the environment.\n\n<b>Sensation</b>\n\nThe skin houses millions of nerve end fibers that detect stimuli and send messages to our brain so that we can feel and respond.\n\n<b>Heat Regulation</b>\n\nOur skin adjust to warm and cool our body.  If our body is hot, we cool ourselves by sweating through our sweat glands.  If we are cold, our blood flow decreases and our vessels constrict. <b> </b>\n\n<b>Excretion</b>\n\nOur sweat glands detoxify our bodies by excreting salt and unwanted toxins via sweat.<b> </b>\n\n<b>Secretion</b>\n\nSebum, secreted through the sebaceous glands helps keep the skin soft, protected and hydrated.  It also lubricates the hair and slows down water evaporation.\n\n<b>Absorption</b>\n\nWhile absorption is limited, our skin can absorb oxygen and discharge carbon dioxide.  It can also produce Vitamin D when exposed to sun.\n\nI think the last function of skin is the impression it gives others so take care of your skin and all of its amazing abilities!  Take care!\n\nKaren\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Functions of Our Skin','','publish','open','open','','functions-of-our-skin','','','2013-12-12 10:45:14','2013-12-12 16:45:14','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=315',0,'post','',0),(316,2,'2013-12-12 10:44:10','2013-12-12 16:44:10','Students learn about Skin Functions','itaskinbeauty.com Blog','','inherit','open','open','','itaskinbeauty-com-blog','','','2013-12-12 10:44:10','2013-12-12 16:44:10','',315,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/itaskinbeauty-com-blog.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(958,2,'2013-12-19 13:43:03','2013-12-19 19:43:03','<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-international-training.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-971\" alt=\"Graduation December 2013 International Training\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-international-training.jpg?w=300\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>Last Saturday (December 14) we held a graduation ceremony for those women, who graduated from Medical Assisting or Esthetics programs since June. It was a small an intimate ceremony, a bit of a change from our last graduation, which was much bigger. Unfortunately, only one esthetics graduate, Laura, was able to come. Several other estheticians and medical assistants had family or work commitments,  which they could not change. Still, in spirit they were all with us.\n\nIt was exciting to see friends and family (parents, siblings, husbands, aunts &amp; uncles, boyfriends, kids, etc.) gather to celebrate women, who have sacrificed so much to attend school and improve their lives!  <a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-esthetics.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-970\" alt=\"Graduation December 2013 Esthetics\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-esthetics.jpg?w=300\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\nBy tradition, we started with playing \"We Are the Champions\" by Queen. Perhaps, no other song captures the spirit of our students so aptly! Among the graduates were women who drove to class from three different States: Illinois, Indiana, and Wisconsin. They all overcame obstacles to earn their certificates: despite health issues, money concerns, tough and demanding jobs, loss of loved ones, they were able to persevere and come out on top!\n\nIt was an emotional ceremony and tears glistened on most eyes. As our president, Dr. Doran, said:\n<blockquote>\"It is a vulnerable time for us. It\'s as with parents when their children leave home; sure, you will come back, but it will be different\"</blockquote>\nWe have another tradition at our school: every graduation we put together a short video to celebrate our students. It is a small gesture meant to remind the graduates about their time at school, and for friends and family to get a peak into what the medical assisting and esthetics programs are like. We hope you enjoy this video:\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rr7HlgF-kTE\n\nAt the end of the class, Dr. Doran typically says: \"Love you, drive safely\". And it was bittersweet to say this one last time to our graduates. We know that the road will take them very far - if they choose to travel. And we are anxiously waiting to hear about their success.\n\n<strong>You can see more photos from our graduation ceremony on our<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.732777526735481.1073741826.135614039785169&amp;type=1&amp;l=c371ae6134\"> Facebook </a> page:</strong>','Graduation for Esthetics and Medical Assisting','','publish','open','open','','graduation-for-esthetics-and-medical-assisting','','','2013-12-19 13:43:03','2013-12-19 19:43:03','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=958',0,'post','',0),(968,2,'2013-12-19 13:23:31','2013-12-19 19:23:31','','Graduation December 2013 134','','inherit','open','open','','graduation-december-2013-134','','','2013-12-19 13:23:31','2013-12-19 19:23:31','',958,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-134.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(969,2,'2013-12-19 13:24:21','2013-12-19 19:24:21','','Graduates December 2013','','inherit','open','open','','graduates-december-2013','','','2013-12-19 13:24:21','2013-12-19 19:24:21','',958,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduates-december-2013.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(970,2,'2013-12-19 13:25:06','2013-12-19 19:25:06','','Graduation December 2013 Esthetics','','inherit','open','open','','graduation-december-2013-esthetics','','','2013-12-19 13:25:06','2013-12-19 19:25:06','',958,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-esthetics.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(971,2,'2013-12-19 13:25:59','2013-12-19 19:25:59','Graduation at International Training Academy','Graduation December 2013 International Training','','inherit','open','open','','graduation-december-2013-international-training','','','2013-12-19 13:25:59','2013-12-19 19:25:59','',958,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/graduation-december-2013-international-training.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(972,2,'2013-12-19 13:26:06','2013-12-19 19:26:06','medical assistant graduating','MA Grad December 2013','','inherit','open','open','','ma-grad-december-2013','','','2013-12-19 13:26:06','2013-12-19 19:26:06','',958,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/ma-grad-december-2013.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1080,2,'2013-12-20 15:57:08','2013-12-20 21:57:08','<strong>Holiday season is supposed to be a joyous time, full of laughter, embraces from the loved ones, and, of course,  gifts!</strong> Yet holidays are also about giving, lending a helping hand to people in need!\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_1087\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"230\"]<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/xmas-tree-international-training-academy.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-1087\" alt=\"Our annual Christmas Tree\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/xmas-tree-international-training-academy.jpg?w=230\" width=\"230\" height=\"300\" /></a> Our annual Christmas Tree[/caption]\n\nEach year, we donate the majority of the profits from our Student Spa to different organizations. In the past,  among others, we supported such great organizations as <a href=\"http://www.livingwellcrc.org/‎\">LivingWell Cancer Resource Center   </a>and <a href=\"www.marklund.org/‎\">Marklund, </a>an organization that serves infants, children, teens and adults with serious and profound developmental disabilities and special healthcare needs.\n\nThis year we have chosen two great causes: the <a href=\"http://www.redcross.org/\">American Red Cross</a> (for the second year in a row) and <a href=\"http://www.10sfighttowin.org\">10s Fight to Win</a>. Here are the reasons why:\n\n<strong>Tragically, each year, thousands people around the world are affected by disasters</strong>: from tornadoes, to hurricanes, to fires, to other tragedies, the list painfully goes on. These people need food, water, first aid, and covers over their heads.\n<blockquote>Each year, the American Red Cross immediately responds to about 70,000 natural and man-made disasters in the U.S., ranging from fires to hurricanes, floods, earthquakes, tornadoes, hazardous materials spills, transportation accidents and explosions.</blockquote>\nThere are, of course, many organizations, which help on the sites of disasters, offering relieve. Yet few have as wide a reach as the Red Cross.\n\n<strong>The second cause we have selected strikes much closer to home. </strong>In late October, we received an email from our amazing alumna Kari. Her daughter, K.K. was diagnosed with a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renal_Medullary_Carcinoma\">Renal Medullary Carcinoma (RMC)</a>, a rare and typically aggressive form of kidney cancer. KK\'s case is extremely unique, and her treatment not only has to be experimental within the context of RMC, such cases typically require a special FDA approval for the individualized approach. Here are some of the reasons why KK\'s case is unprecedented:\n<ul>\n	<li>RMC is rarely diagnosed in Caucasians.</li>\n	<li>She does not possess Sickle Cell, a trait that goes almost exclusively with RMC</li>\n	<li>RMC is rarely diagnosed in women.</li>\n	<li>KK was diagnosed at a non-metastatic stage, which is very unsual (and hopeful).</li>\n	<li>RMC shows resistance to conventional chemotherapy.</li>\n</ul>\nWe are in awe of KK\'s bravery and her fight against RMC!\n\nTeam KK have set up a great <a href=\"www.10sfighttowin.org\">website</a>, which talks about RMC and her story. As you can imagine, the costs of medical care are very high. So Team KK are trying to raise funds to help pay medical bills and expenses not covered by her insurance.<strong> We know that KK is not just ready for the fight - she is going to win!</strong>\n\n<strong><em>In closing, we hope that you will spend the holidays, surrounded by your friends and family! And as you celebrate the arrival of the New Year, don\'t forget to share some of your good fortune with others!</em></strong>','Holidays and the Importance of Giving','','publish','open','open','','holidays-and-the-importance-of-giving','','','2013-12-20 15:57:08','2013-12-20 21:57:08','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1080',0,'post','',0),(1087,2,'2013-12-20 15:53:04','2013-12-20 21:53:04','Holiday Celebration - International Training Academy','Xmas Tree - International Training Academy','Our annual Christmas Tree','inherit','open','open','','xmas-tree-international-training-academy','','','2013-12-20 15:53:04','2013-12-20 21:53:04','',1080,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/xmas-tree-international-training-academy.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1574,2,'2013-12-26 11:58:23','2013-12-26 17:58:23','','Happy Holidays 2013','','inherit','open','open','','happy-holidays-2013','','','2013-12-26 11:58:23','2013-12-26 17:58:23','',1575,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/happy-holidays-2013.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1575,2,'2013-12-24 12:15:14','2013-12-24 18:15:14','<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/happy-holidays-2013.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1574\" alt=\"Happy Holidays 2013\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/happy-holidays-2013.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"707\" /></a>','Happy Holidays from International Training Academy!','','publish','open','open','','happy-holidays-from-international-training-academy','','','2013-12-24 12:15:14','2013-12-24 18:15:14','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1575',0,'post','',0),(1587,2,'2013-12-26 14:45:40','2013-12-26 20:45:40','<b>Press release: <i>For immediate release</i></b>\n\n<b>100 Scholarships for Laid-Off Dominick’s Workers</b>\n\n<i>Schaumburg, IL - December 26, 2013</i>. <strong>Deeply moved by the plight of Illinois workers, laid off by Dominick’s, International Training Academy has announced today that it will award 100 vocational scholarships worth <a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/100-scholarships-itaskinbeauty.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1588\" alt=\"scholarships-dominick\'s\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/100-scholarships-itaskinbeauty.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"348\" /></a>$1,000 each.</strong>\n\n“We are known as the school of second chance”, said Academy’s president, Dr. Natalia Doran, “and, having helped hundreds of people change their lives through education, we want to help these men and women start the new year with renewed hope about the future”.\n\nDominick\'s Finer Foods, Inc., owned by Safeway Inc., revealed in October that it was closing all of its 72 stores in the Chicago area by the end of this year, leaving thousands of workers unemployed.\n\nInternational Training Academy is an elite vocational school, which offers skin- and health care training programs. The Academy has trained hundreds of students, ranging in age from 18 to 63, including immigrants from 27 countries. It holds multiple licenses and is approved to operate by IDFPR and PBVS Division of IBHE; it is also approved as a sponsor for GI Bill and WIA benefits.\n<p align=\"center\"><b>###</b></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Contact person: Anastasia Usova</b>\n\nCompany name: International Training Academy\n\nTelephone number: (847)995-1932\n\nFax number: (847)995-1936\n\nEmail address: manager@itaskinbeauty.com\n\nWebsite address: <a href=\"http://www.itaSkinBeauty.com\">www.itaSkinBeauty.com</a>','100 Scholarships for Laid-off Dominick\'s Workers','','publish','open','open','','100-scholarships-for-laid-off-dominicks-workers','','','2013-12-26 14:45:40','2013-12-26 20:45:40','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1587',0,'post','',1),(1588,2,'2013-12-26 14:43:28','2013-12-26 20:43:28','100 Scholarships $1,000 each to laid-off Dominick\'s employees','100 Scholarships itaskinbeauty','','inherit','open','open','','100-scholarships-itaskinbeauty','','','2013-12-26 14:43:28','2013-12-26 20:43:28','',1587,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/100-scholarships-itaskinbeauty.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1592,2,'2013-12-27 17:23:05','2013-12-27 23:23:05','Yesterday, we have sent out a <a href=\"http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/2013/12/26/100-scholarships-for-laid-off-dominicks-workers/\">press release</a>, announcing that we would award $1,000 scholarships to workers, laid off by Dominick\'s. The response has been tremendous! We heard from a representative of Dominick\'s, who offered to share the information with the workers.\n\nToday, we were very excited to receive a call from <a href=\"http://abclocal.go.com/wls/bio?section=resources/inside_station/newsteam&amp;id=8599101\">Diane Pathieu</a>, a reporter for ABC7 Chicago. She was doing a story on how the closure of Dominick\'s stores will affect over 5,000 workers and invited to share how we want to help.\n\nAgain, we know that it is a difficult time for thousands of people affected. But we hope that this difficult time will become an opportunity for many to change their lives, and pursue the careers with security.\nYou can watch the video <a href=\"http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&amp;id=9373993\">here</a>:\n','Interview with ABC7 Chicago','','publish','open','open','','interview-with-abc7-chicago','','','2013-12-27 17:23:05','2013-12-27 23:23:05','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1592',0,'post','',0),(1601,2,'2013-12-31 20:13:39','2014-01-01 02:13:39','<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/img_20131230_122327.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-1602 alignright\" alt=\"flower_intl_academy\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/img_20131230_122327.jpg\" width=\"400\" height=\"533\" /></a>A curious thing occurred in our school on the eve of the New Year: a plant that we have kept more out of habit than hope, has bloomed and given us two beautiful flowers to admire!\n\nThe weather hasn\'t been gentle, dropping to 8° Fahrenheit yesterday. But over the past year, Dr. Doran has watered and nourished the plant; and her care has been vindicated. It is not a stretch to compare this to our students. We try to nourish them, give them love, care, and knowledge- and when they graduate and truly \"bloom\", we can only admire the result.\n\nAs this new year knocks on your door, we hope that you and your loved ones take care of each other! May this year bring you happiness and success in every endeavor!\n\n<strong>From the bottom of our hearts, we wish you a HAPPY NEW YEAR!</strong>','Love, Care, and a Happy New Year!','','publish','open','open','','love-care-and-a-happy-new-year','','','2013-12-31 20:13:39','2014-01-01 02:13:39','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1601',0,'post','',0),(1602,2,'2013-12-30 12:28:27','2013-12-30 18:28:27','Flower blooming at International Training Academy','flower_intl_academy','','inherit','open','open','','img_20131230_122327','','','2013-12-30 12:28:27','2013-12-30 18:28:27','',1601,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/img_20131230_122327.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1613,2,'2014-01-05 16:21:01','2014-01-05 22:21:01','Tomorrow was supposed to be the first day of class after the Winter Break! We have been preparing and anxiously waiting to welcome our students back to the school!\n\nUnfortunately, Mother Nature had other plans for Chicago and surrounding areas.  the <a href=\"http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?zoneid=ILZ014&amp;zflg=1\">National Weather Service</a> is predicting hazardous weather outlook, with record breaking low temperatures:\n<blockquote><b>Monday: </b>Windy. Partly cloudy. Areas of blowing snow. Very cold with record breaking temperatures likely. Temperatures nearly steady around 13 to 17 below. Wind chills as low as 35 below to 45 below zero. West winds 20 to 30 mph until late afternoon decreasing to 15 to 25 mph late in the afternoon. Gusts up to 40 mph.\n\n<b>Monday Night: </b>Partly cloudy in the evening then clearing. Bitterly cold. Lows 14 to 18 below. Wind chills as low as 35 below to 45 below zero. West winds 10 to 20 mph with gusts up to 30 mph.</blockquote>\nAt our school, we believe that the educational process must go on, no matter what! Yet the safety of our students is still paramount. With this, we are cancelling our Monday classes.\n\nWe hope that the weather improves enough for us to start classes on Tuesday.  In the meantime, please stay safe and warm! And don\'t drive, unless you absolutely have to!','Classes Cancelled for Monday (January 6)','','publish','open','open','','classes-cancelled-for-monday-january-6','','','2014-01-05 16:21:01','2014-01-05 22:21:01','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1613',0,'post','',0),(1624,2,'2014-01-21 11:10:02','2014-01-21 17:10:02','Starting something new is something scary. <strong>But if you are willing to extend your hand and reach out for the handle,  you can open the door to real success!</strong>\n\nWe are very excited to again offer our Medical Assisting Program on <strong>February 10, 2014</strong>. In a span of only <strong>18 weeks</strong>, students will receive world-class training in FOUR specialties. The graduates of this phenomenal program work with<b> top plastic surgeons </b>and <b>dermatologists</b>, and at<b> leading hospitals under renowned dermatology professors</b>!\n\n<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/medical-assisting-feb-10-start-ita.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1625\" alt=\"MA-Classes-February-10\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/medical-assisting-feb-10-start-ita.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"664\" /></a>','Open Door to Success wtih Medical Assisting','','publish','open','open','','open-door-to-success-wtih-medical-assisting','','','2014-01-21 11:10:02','2014-01-21 17:10:02','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1624',0,'post','',0),(1625,2,'2014-01-21 10:43:18','2014-01-21 16:43:18','Medical Assisting program at International Training Academy. February 10 Start','Medical Assisting - Feb 10 Start - ITA','','inherit','open','open','','medical-assisting-feb-10-start-ita','','','2014-01-21 10:43:18','2014-01-21 16:43:18','',1624,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/medical-assisting-feb-10-start-ita.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1628,2,'2014-01-24 09:12:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Dry vs. Dehydrated Skin','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-01-24 09:12:45','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1628',0,'post','',0),(1629,2,'2014-01-24 09:27:05','2014-01-24 15:27:05','<strong>Here is another post from our wonderful Esthetics student Karen, who has been quickly progressing in her studies: </strong>\n\nIn Chicago today it was 5 degrees.  Ugh!  It has really been terrible both on driving and the skin!  Along with the temperature drop comes dry, tight skin.  What is going on with our skin?  Is it dry?  Is it dehydrated?  Before starting esthetics school, I thought dry and dehydrated skin were pretty much the same and that if your skin was dehydrated it meant you needed to drink more water.  Wrong.\n\nIn class we have learned that dry and dehydrated skin have different underlying problems and need to be treated very differently.\n\n<b>Dry Skin:  </b>First, Dry skin is a skin <i>type</i>.  It  is alipidic, meaning it lacks oil.  Dry skin is often the result of hormones and is mostly seen in mature skin.  As we age our skin produces less oil and dead skin cells do not shed as often leading to dry skin.  Healthy skin requires oil to protect and hydrate our skin.  It is very important to the health of our skin.  Without oil our skin is unable to hold in moisture.  Without oil our skin\'s natural barrier function (a protective barrier of  oil and sweat that protects and nourishes our skin) is damaged which not only leads to dry skin but also sensitivity and inflammation - which then lead to premature aging).  <i>Dry skin requires oil! </i>\n\n<b>What can help dry skin?</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Regular facial massage to encourage oil production .</li>\n	<li>Using moisturizers containing occlusive ingredients that will hold moisture in and create a barrier to reduce water loss and prevent dry skin.</li>\n	<li>Using creamy, non-foaming,  cleansers</li>\n	<li>Using serums under moisturizer that contain water binding properties to help hold and attract moisture (for example hyaluronic acid and glycerin).</li>\n	<li>Chemical exfoliants to help shed dead cells, promote cell renewal  and encourage product penetration.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Dehydrated Skin:  </b>Dehydrated skin is a skin <i>condition</i>.  It lacks water.  Anyone can have dehydrated skin, including oily skin.  Dehydrated skin can be caused by the extreme weather (for example, 5 degree temps!), by the environment, by hormonal imbalances or by products we use on our skin (think foaming, harsh cleansers and alcohol based toners).  Dehydrated skin can feel tight and deflated and is often irritated (red) and <a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/facial-procedures-3.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-1630\" alt=\"Facial Procedures (3)\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/facial-procedures-3.jpg?w=500\" width=\"350\" height=\"466\" /></a>sensitive.  The texture of dehydrated skin is typically rough and has fine lines due to lack of water.   <i>Dehydrated skin requires water!</i>\n\n<b>What can help Dehydrated Skin?</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Using moisturizers and serums containing humectants which are ingredients that attract water.  (for example hyaluronic acid and glycerin).   These ingredients will help hydrate the skin.</li>\n	<li>Using mild, non foaming cleansers (avoid soap and other alkaline products!)</li>\n	<li>Using hydrating, soothing masks to rebalance skin.</li>\n</ul>\nAt school we have learned that the best defense against both dry and dehydrated skin is a good daily skin routine that is specific to your skin type or condition.  By using products specific for your skin type or condition on a daily basis, both dry and dehydrated skin can become balanced, healthy, glowing skin!\n\nAll the best!\n\nKaren.','Combating the Dehydrated Skin','','publish','open','open','','combating-the-dehydrated-skin','','','2014-01-24 09:27:05','2014-01-24 15:27:05','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1629',0,'post','',2),(1630,2,'2014-01-24 09:25:05','2014-01-24 15:25:05','','Facial Procedures (3)','','inherit','open','open','','facial-procedures-3','','','2014-01-24 09:25:05','2014-01-24 15:25:05','',1629,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/facial-procedures-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1636,2,'2014-02-04 14:26:11','2014-02-04 20:26:11','It is no secret that our school is truly international, having educated students from almost 30 countries. But it\'s not just students who immigrated to the United States, who are interested in our program! Recently, we have received a lot of messages and calls from around the world, asking how they can study at International Training Academy.\n\nBelow, we have outlined the steps that an international student needs to take if they are interested in pursuing training with us.\n\n<b>1: Admission</b>\n\nObviously a student in another country cannot simply schedule  a school visit. However, we still believe in getting to know the student - and allowing them to learn as much as possible about the school before making this decision! We are able to organize teleconference sessions via Skype and Google Chat. Other arrangements can be made, as well.\nOnce you decide that our school is a right fit for you, you can apply for admission.\n\n<b>2: Documents for Admission</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Copy of Passport (should be valid for at least 6 months beyond your intended period of study in the United States)</li>\n	<li>Financial evidence that shows you or your sponsor has sufficient funds to cover your tuition and living expenses during the period of your intended stay</li>\n	<li>Copy of High School or University Diploma (translated into English)</li>\n</ul>\nIf you have a spouse and/or children who are going to accompany you while in the US, you will need to provide the following documents in order to submit each dependent’s I-20:\n<ul>\n	<li>Proof of your relationship to your spouse and/or children (e.g., marriage and/or birth certificates translated into English.)</li>\n	<li>Copy of Passport for each dependent (should be valid for at least 6 months beyond your intended period of study in the United States)</li>\n</ul>\n<b>3: School Fees</b>\n\nYou need to pay the following fees:\n<ul>\n	<li>Application Fee: $160</li>\n	<li>Shipping Fee: $100 (delivery within 2-5 days)</li>\n</ul>\n<b>4: I-20 Form</b>\n\nAfter we have reviewed your application and determined that you meet all the (academic and financial) standards for admission, the Designated School Official (DSO) at International Training Academy will issue you a SEVIS I-20 form.\n\n<b>5: SEVIS Fee</b>\n\nAfter you have received your form I-20, you must pay a $200 SEVIS I-901 fee. You may <a title=\"Student and Exchange Visitor Program SEVIS I-901 Fee\" href=\"https://www.fmjfee.com/i901fee/\">pay online</a> (https://www.fmjfee.com/i901fee/index.jsp ) or ask International Skin Beauty Academy for assistance. Please keep your receipt, and bring it to your visa interview.\n\n<b>6: Visa Interview</b>\n\nYou will need to contact the <a title=\"U.S. Embassy\" href=\"http://www.usembassy.gov/\">U.S. Embassy</a> (http://www.usembassy.gov/) in your country and apply for a visa interview. You must take the following documents with you to the interview:\n<ul>\n	<li>Form I-20, properly signed by the DSO and by you</li>\n	<li>Financial evidence that shows you or your sponsor has sufficient funds to cover your tuition and living expenses during the period of your intended stay</li>\n	<li>Evidence of intent to depart the U.S. after completion of studies</li>\n	<li>Passport (should be valid for at least 6 months beyond your intended period of study in the United States)</li>\n	<li>Proof of payment SEVIS I-901 fee</li>\n	<li>Form DS-160</li>\n	<li>Photograph(s)</li>\n	<li>Proof of Payment for the Visa Interview Fee of $160</li>\n	<li>School Information</li>\n	<li>Home Accommodations</li>\n</ul>\n<b>7: Departure Preparation   </b>\n\nAfter the U.S. Embassy grants you an M-1 visa your next step is to prepare yourself for departure. Provide the following information to International Skin Beauty Academy admissions representative:\n<ul>\n	<li>Flight Information: Let us know the date and time when you will be arriving in the U.S. and your flight number.</li>\n	<li>Tell us if you would like to be picked up at the airport. An additional fee will apply.</li>\n	<li>Tell us if you would like housing assistance.</li>\n</ul>\nRemember: You cannot arrive in the United States more than 30 days prior to the start date of your classes.\n\n<b>8: Admission to the United States in M-1 Status</b>\n\nUpon arrival at the U.S. port of entry, you need to proceed to the terminal area for arriving passengers. Have the following documents available for presentation:\n<ul>\n	<li>Form I-20, properly signed by the DSO and by you.</li>\n	<li>Passport valid for at least six months.</li>\n	<li>M-1 visa. For initial entries, the name of the school on the M-1 visa must match the name of the school on your Form I-20.</li>\n	<li>Evidence of financial support, including the same financial support information used to obtain the M-1 visa.</li>\n</ul>\nIn certain cases, you may have to provide proof of having paid the SEVIS fee.\n\n<b>9: I-94 (Arrival/Departure Record) and I-20 Forms</b>\n\nOnce your inspection is successfully completed, the customs officer will:\n<ul>\n	<li>Stamp your SEVIS Form I-20 for duration of status (“D/S”) for F visa holders</li>\n	<li>Stamp the Arrival-Departure Record Form (I-94) and staple it in the passport</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>If you have additional questions, please contact us via our <a href=\"http://itaskinbeauty.com/contact/\">website</a>: http://itaskinbeauty.com/contact/</strong>\n\n&nbsp;','Application Process for International Students','','publish','open','open','','application-process-for-international-students','','','2014-02-04 14:26:11','2014-02-04 20:26:11','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1636',0,'post','',0),(1641,2,'2014-02-05 13:23:13','2014-02-05 19:23:13','<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-ita-blog.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1642\" alt=\"Karen ITA Blog\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-ita-blog.jpg\" width=\"328\" height=\"490\" /></a><strong>Here\'s the latest blog post from our Esthetics student, Karen:</strong>\n\nWeek 22 - 5 Weeks Left!\n\nInstead of cozying up on the coach and watching a show with my family last night, I was upstairs drawing eyebrows on my arm and practicing my eyebrow waxing technique.  There is a point to this.  I promise.\n\nTime has been moving quickly.  Suddenly, it is February 4th and I have 5 weeks of school left.  In clinic we have been perfecting our facial and waxing techniques.  We have also learned some new machines and some new techniques such as hot stone therapy, aromatherapy and body wraps.  The result:  I am now completely hairless and have glowing skin!\n\nSeriously though, the past 22 weeks have been extremely rewarding.  I have met many new friends and have learned a ton.  But, they have not been without a lot of sacrifice, hard work and commitment.  Being successful at something does not come easy.  There have been many occasions,  I have had to move out of my comfort zone and face the fear failure, face not succeeding.  But, I have always been driven to be the best  in my past careers and in my triathlon racing.\n\nEsthetics school is no different.  I want to be the best.  I chose<a title=\"Application Process for International Students\" href=\"http://www.itaSkinBeauty.com\"> ISBA</a> because I want to be the best and they are the best school.  But, with just under 5 weeks left to go, I find myself struggling and wondering I have made the right decision and if I am good enough to succeed in school and in this industry.  Do I have what it takes to be successful?  Am I good enough?  Though I have been working super hard both at school and at home, my stomach is in knots as I have not achieved advanced status - which means my skills are strong enough to work on clients.  I know I will ultimately finish school, but for me, even with a license, if I don\'t finish as an advanced student I will feel like I have failed - both myself and my family.  I am not sure what I will do if I fail.  I had planned to work in a medical setting and possibly pursue and medical  assistance program but, not being an advance student yet, I fear I am not good enough.  This being my biggest fear, is driving me to work even harder.\n\nIf you are reading this blog and are thinking of going to esthetics school, be prepared to put yourself out there each and every day.  Be prepared to work hard and learn new skills.  Be prepared to do what it takes to succeed whether it is extra hours of practice, practicing at home or… even drawing eyebrows on your arms.  ;)\n\nAll the best, Karen','Student\'s Journey Coming to an End','','publish','open','open','','students-journey','','','2014-02-05 13:23:13','2014-02-05 19:23:13','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1641',0,'post','',0),(1642,2,'2014-02-05 11:44:50','2014-02-05 17:44:50','','Karen ITA Blog','','inherit','open','open','','karen-ita-blog','','','2014-02-05 11:44:50','2014-02-05 17:44:50','',1641,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-ita-blog.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1644,2,'2014-02-11 09:58:13','2014-02-11 15:58:13','<strong>Today we have a rare treat for you - two very different, both equally wonderful, stories of our students. </strong>\n\n<strong>The first one has been generously shared by our wonderful student, Carol. She is nearing the end of her esthetics training, and has taken a look at some of the proud accomplishments in the program, and the change of goals.</strong> <strong>Like many students who worked for years before deciding to pursue esthetics, Carol had been anxious about going back to school. Here\'s her story:</strong>\n\nI am currently a student at ISBA. I have always had an interest in skin care, makeup, beauty treatments, products and ingredients. I make a habit to read the labels on the skin and beauty products I use. Since school I have learned even more about which ingredients are actually beneficial to the skin and body and which ones simply are added to give the product a better texture, scent or appearance. I really enjoy helping others, whether it be to help teach them something, help them feel better about themselves as a person, to help them look their best, to help them reduce stress, or help them decide what products to purchase based on their individual needs. I decided to go to school for Esthetics since there are so may career options in the field of Esthetics and Medical Esthetics. Someone could work in a medical office, salon, or spa, cosmetic or skin care sales, be a makeup artist, teacher, product developer, researcher just to name a few! Dr. Doran and her staff of teachers are so knowledgeable. I am a naturally curious person. I always ask a lot of questions in class, but that is how you learn. I always want to know why and how. Dr.Doran and the other teachers always take the time to answer all my questions.\n\nYesterday (on Monday) I earned 100% on the Advanced Treatments chapter test! It’s only the 2<sup>nd</sup> time I’ve done that, but since attending this school my lowest test score was 85%. Believe me school, does not come easy for me! It’s hard work, and I make flash cards for every chapter to study and test myself with. My classmates have helped me learn also, and I have have met some wonderful women who inspire me so much! In practical class I enjoy giving (and getting) facial massages, since the power of touch benefits both the client and the Esthetician! In today’s world people are so stressed! I find it rewarding when the person I’m massaging falls asleep, as I know I helped them relax and hopefully forget their problems for a while. It’s funny because I went into this school thinking I want to work with lasers, microdermabrasion, and the latest technology and machines in a medical setting. Now I find myself drawn towards natural, plant-based ingredients, anti oxidants, humectants, and essential oils. I’m leaning toward becoming a manufacturers representative, sales rep, or a researcher. Our school also does charity work for Cancer patients. This really touches my heart since I lost my father to lung cancer a few years ago. I pray he is looking down on me, and that I can make him proud and succeed!\n\n<strong>Check back later today to read about Alissa\'s new journey!\nIf you decide that you yourself want to go back to school, take the first step and<a href=\"http://itaskinbeauty.com/contact/\"> contact us </a>today. Classes start on March 10. </strong>\n\n---------------------\n\n<strong>While Carol is nearing the end of her education, Alissa is just taking her first steps.</strong> <strong>This is what she shared with us after her first class on Monday:</strong>\n<div>\n<div>Until my senior year of high school, I had no idea what an Esthetician even was; now here I am at an Esthetician school. It\'s funny just how much can change over a year.</div>\nI had to work hard and save up to be able to attend this school. I am more than happy to be here; it still does not feel real to me.</div>\nWhen I found out what an Esthetician was, I immediately loved it. I found what I wanted to do. I looked into several schools, but ISBA was the best. I felt welcome here, and I still do. I feel this school has the proper amount of discipline to prepare their students for their careers. The other schools I visited did not seem to care as much about student success. I know this has only been my first day here, but that is the point. I felt like I was going to be successful here even before I started. Tomorrow the makeup instructor is joining us and will be teaching more about makeup application. I am still trying to take all the information from my first day in, but I can\'t wait to learn more.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Carol\'s Story & Alissa\'s Story (Updated)','','publish','open','open','','students-story','','','2014-02-11 09:58:13','2014-02-11 15:58:13','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1644',0,'post','',0),(1654,2,'2014-02-14 16:52:33','2014-02-14 22:52:33','<strong>To honor the spirit of Valentine\'s Day, we have spent it with the people we love - our students! We hope that today - and every day - you remember to tell your loved ones how you really feel about them! </strong>\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1655\" alt=\"Happy Valentines Day ITA\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/happy-valentines-day-ita.png?w=500\" width=\"500\" height=\"401\" /><strong>With love,</strong>\n\n<strong>~ International Training Academy</strong>','Happy Valentine\'s Day!','','publish','open','open','','happy-valentines-day','','','2014-02-14 16:52:33','2014-02-14 22:52:33','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1654',0,'post','',0),(1655,2,'2014-02-14 16:49:08','2014-02-14 22:49:08','','Happy Valentines Day ITA','','inherit','open','open','','happy-valentines-day-ita','','','2014-02-14 16:49:08','2014-02-14 22:49:08','',1654,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/happy-valentines-day-ita.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1659,2,'2014-02-17 11:08:40','2014-02-17 17:08:40','<img src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/happy-presidents-day.png\" class=\"size-full\" alt=\"Happy President\'s Day!\" />\n\n<p>Today is the President\'s Day (also known as Washington\'s Birthday and Lincoln\'s Birthday). We invite you to celebrate the opportunities!</p>','Happy President\'s Day!','','publish','open','open','','happy-presidents-day','','','2014-02-17 11:08:40','2014-02-17 17:08:40','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1659',0,'post','',0),(1661,2,'2014-02-18 10:58:48','2014-02-18 16:58:48','<strong>A week ago, a young woman started her journey to becoming a skin care professional! She has been busy with classes, but has carved out a little time to write an update on her experience. Below is the second post from our new Esthetics student, Alissa:</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"520\"]<a href=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/esthetics-jan-feb-2014-006.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image  \" id=\"i-1663\" alt=\"Makeup Training International Skin Beauty Academy\" src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/esthetics-jan-feb-2014-006.jpg?w=650\" width=\"520\" height=\"348\" /></a> Makeup Class[/caption]\n\nThis week was the start of my second week attending ISBA. For makeup, I have learned the basics. So much goes into the basics, so much detail. Makeup is not an easy thing to learn. I still have two more practical days of makeup before we start the next unit. On my third day at ISBA, we did back treatments. Only on other students, of course. I was rather nervous, but was talked through it.The other students are so nice and helpful. Also, it feels kind of nice to say that on my third day I was already doing things that I wanted to learn. Today we did a review on the makeup book work and microdermabrasion was practiced. Me and two others were the clients as the rest took turns practicing certain parts of the procedure. My face feels so soft, it\'s not even funny. By the end of this week, I hope to have a better grasp on makeup application.','Student\'s Story: Things You Learn in a Week','','publish','open','open','','students-story-things-you-learn-in-a-week','','','2014-02-18 10:58:48','2014-02-18 16:58:48','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1661',0,'post','',0),(1669,2,'2014-02-21 16:10:29','2014-02-21 22:10:29','<b><span style=\"font-size:large;\">Get your skills and career to the next level with our continuing education classes! Register for our our spectacular 60-hour CE Clinical/Medical Esthetics Program - and open the doors of best medical offices and medispas! </span></b>\n\n<b>The World of Medical Esthetics, Skin\'s Ageing Mechanisms, and Manual Lymph Drainage (A1)</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, March 22</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $290</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Skin Analysis vs. Skin Conditions, Acne Clients\' Concerns, Rosacea Disease vs. Sensitivity, and OSHA Standards (A2)     </b>      <a href=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/may-2013-001-copy.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-large wp-image-190\" alt=\"Facial Demonstration International Training Academy\" src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/may-2013-001-copy.jpg?w=500\" width=\"500\" height=\"214\" /></a>\n<ul>\n	<li>Sunday, March 23</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $290</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Peeling the Age Off (What to Expect from Chemical Exfoliation), Microdermabrasion, and Waxing (B1)    </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, March 29</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $290</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Electrotherapy, Cosmeceuticals &amp; Botanicals, and Making Sense of Scents with Aromatherapy </b><b>(B2)</b>\n<ul>\n	<li> Sunday, March 30</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $290</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Laser Treatments - Hands-on with Fastest Laser for Hair Removal (Presented by AMMP) (C1 )</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, April 05</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $750</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Injectables (Botox®, Fillers); Therapeutic Relaxation - Hands &amp; Feet (C2 )      </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Sunday, April 06</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 5:00 PM</li>\n	<li>10 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $390</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Chemical Peels and Microdermabrasion: What to Expect and What Could Go Wrong                       </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, April 05</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 1:15 PM</li>\n	<li>5 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $150</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Waxing from Basic to Advanced</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, April 26</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 1:15 PM</li>\n	<li>5 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $150</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Perfect Eyebrow: Tint, Wax, Draw            </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, April 26</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 1:15 PM</li>\n	<li>5 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $150</li>\n</ul>\n<b>No Vichy shower?  No problem!  Body Wraps. </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Sunday, April 06</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 1:15 PM</li>\n	<li>5 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $150</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Skin Analysis Made Simple: Skin types vs Skin Conditions         </b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Saturday, May 10</li>\n	<li>Time: 9:00 AM- 1:15 PM</li>\n	<li>5 CEUs</li>\n	<li>Cost: $150</li>\n</ul>\n<b><span style=\"font-size:large;\">Call us at 847-995-1932 with any questions or to reserve your spot!</span></b>','NEW CE Classes & Clinical/Medical Esthetics!','','publish','open','open','','continuing-education','','','2014-02-21 16:10:29','2014-02-21 22:10:29','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1669',0,'post','',0),(1672,2,'2014-02-24 18:48:35','2014-02-25 00:48:35','<div>\n\n<strong>Here\'s the weekly update from our lovely student Alissa, who is now in the 3rd week of classes (time sure flies!):</strong>\n\nOnward I go, to the third week of school. Today was the chapter test on makeup. I have not seen a test formatted quite like here. It is a form of scan-tron, but not something I have come across in high school. The test was 50 questions, which really is not bad at all compared to what I was used to taking. Some of the questions are worded strangely, but it is for our benefit. The tests they give are supposed to be harder than the state exam. Anyway, right after everyone finishes, we trade and grade. I like this because you know how you did right away. So I know I did very well :).\n\nMakeup application is not my forte, but it is still something I enjoy and have enjoyed learning. After the last day of makeup last week, I would not say I feel ready to be paid to do a bride\'s makeup, but I feel much more confident than I did starting. On the last day of makeup, we did an activity where we do other students makeup according to a magazine picture they have chosen. It was a lot of fun. Going into this, you must understand that your face will not magically reform its shape and colors to look just like the female pictured. So obviously someone with deep brown eyes who has a picture of a girl with blue eyes will not magically obtain blue eyes from the makeup application. Also, thinking makeup colors, blue eyes are brought out by shadows with yellow and/or red undertones. Brown eyes can take most all colors, but it won\'t bring the color out the same as it would for blue eyes.  My partner matched the makeup from the picture I had very well, and I was so happy with how it looked.\n\nBefore getting back to what we learned today, last week a Bioelements educator came in. We got two packets, one that was big and one that was really big. These packets have all the Bioelements products, except for the ones that are to be released this year. We went through each one, what it does, what ingredients are in the products, what each ingredient does, etc. It was a lot to take in, but thankfully we were able to keep these packets.\n\nGetting back to today, after the test we started learning about resumes and cover letters. Even if you have one already, the information is more than helpful. At least I found it to be. Today was also a lot to take in, but we have minimal homework this week. I am eager  to learn business plans on Wednesday.\n\n</div>','Student\'s Story - Week 3','','publish','open','open','','students-story-week-3','','','2014-02-24 18:48:35','2014-02-25 00:48:35','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1672',0,'post','',0),(1676,2,'2014-02-28 14:38:31','2014-02-28 20:38:31','<p><strong>Here\'s another blog post from our wonderful student Karen: </strong></p><p><b>Makeup Class</b></p><p>Last week we finished our makeup certification with Ms. Nancy Jackson.  It was a fun two weeks filled with lots of makeup tips and useful tricks.  Miss Nancy brought a ton of products and lots of brushes for use to try.  Though I love makeup, I don\'t think I was that great at makeup application.  I think I need some work.  There were some girls that really had a natural ability to make any girl they worked with look amazing. Luckily, as the picture shows below, I was fortunate to have a girl who had a natural ability to look good regardless of my work on her.  Got to love beautiful Manal (pictured to the right). <a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1680\" alt=\"ISBA makeup class ILlinois\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup1.jpg\" width=\"497\" height=\"338\" /></a></p><p><b>We learned a ton but here are the <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">basics</span> I took away when applying makeup:</b></p><p>1.  Apply Moisturizer to allow foundation to go on smoothly<br /> 2.  Apply primer to entire face.  Don\'t skip!  Primer makes everything smooth and also helps makeup last longer.<br /> 3.  Apply concealer on under eyes and also on any red areas and blemishes.  Concealer can also work to highlight so focus on the center of the face to brighten for example, sides of nose and forehead.<br /> 4.  Blend in concealer with a brush.<br /> 5.  Apply an eye primer to lid and blend in.<br /> 6.  Apply eye color.  Apply a base color (a light color) on entire lid first.<br /> 7.  Apply darker color in crease and on outer third of the lid in a side \"V\"<br /> 8.  Make sure to blend eye colors with a blending brush so color does not look too dark, blotchy or harsh.<br /> 9.  Line eyes.  For a soft subtle look, apply shadow or pencil to lash line and under eye. Blend.<br /> For a bolder look, use liquid liner.</p><p>10.  Apply a subtle highlight color to brow bone.<br /> 11.  Fill in brows with pencil or powder.  Avoid matching your brows to your hair color exactly.    For blondes, go two shades darker.  For brunettes, go a shade or two lighter than hair color.<br /> 12.  Curl Lashes<br /> 13.  Apply mascara<br /> 14.  Attach Falsies with glue.  Let dry before moving on to next step.<br /> 15.  Touch up eye liner to hide any glue from false lashes<br /> 16.  Contour face using a matte brown shade.  Miss Nancy swears by \"Too Faced\".  Contour the side of nose, under cheeks, jaw line, and top and sides of forehead.<br /> 17.  Apply color to cheeks<br /> 18.  Apply color to lips</p><p><b>The end result!</b></p><p><a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup-2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-large wp-image-1677 alignleft\" alt=\"makeup-international-skin-beauty-academy\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup-2.jpg?w=500\" width=\"500\" height=\"371\" /></a></p>','Learning Makeup','','publish','open','open','','learning-makeup','','','2014-02-28 14:38:31','2014-02-28 20:38:31','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1676',0,'post','',0),(1677,2,'2014-02-28 14:34:12','2014-02-28 20:34:12','','Karen Makeup 2','','inherit','open','open','','karen-makeup-2','','','2014-02-28 14:34:12','2014-02-28 20:34:12','',1676,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1680,2,'2014-02-28 14:38:09','2014-02-28 20:38:09','','Karen Makeup','','inherit','open','open','','karen-makeup','','','2014-02-28 14:38:09','2014-02-28 20:38:09','',1676,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/karen-makeup1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1684,2,'2014-03-03 18:33:08','2014-03-04 00:33:08','<strong>Here\'s another post from our lovely Esthetics student, Alissa!</strong>\n\nI have completed 3 weeks of school already. For me it still feels like a blessing to be there. I wake up, and it brings a smile on my face to know I am going to school. I cannot say that about high school.  Last week Thursday was probably the last time I would see a lot of the group of graduates.  Thankfully, I got their phone numbers :).  I wish them all good luck! (<strong>And all of you will be missed!</strong>)\n\nAnyway, Tuesday was a big day for me. I was asked to be a model  for a Brazilian.  For those who do not already know, it is where all the hair…down there… is waxed. Because the student\'s final test on Brazilian waxing  was coming soon, I agreed. She could not believe at first that I agreed to it because it was my first time. I figured it was OK because I would get it done by someone about to graduate, who has already performed the procedure before. I’m not going to sugar-coat it. It was manageable, but it hurt more than I thought it would. It did produce some tears at one point. The girls were very nice though. A couple of them were by my side most of the time trying to distract and comfort me. There are some benefits to being the baby of the group :).  It was also a bit uncomfortable because there were others present. I understand this is all for the benefit of learning, and everyone will have to do it at some point.  Maybe by the end of my schooling I will barely feel the waxing.\n\nWednesday was learning business plan. This was also quite a lot to take in. Some things seem like common sense, but they are things you really need to think in depth about. Simple questions like “How much time can I put into the business?”  How many hours of needed things, such as sleep, eating, going to the bathroom, shopping for what is needed, etc?  Without a job, and getting about 7 hours of sleep per night, leaving other variables to 4 hours leaves you with 16 hours per day that you can put into said business. Again, another common sense thing, but one has to be very realistic when thinking about these things. The new girls and I have a project to do this week; create a resume, cover letter, and business plan.\n\nThursday, I couldn’t believe Dr. Doran and Ms. Carrie taught us group of newbs to wax. We only did legs, but it was actually really fun. I was very excited. It was not a detailed lesson from the book. It was just the basics of how to apply soft wax on the legs. I can’t wait to learn more!!!\n\nWith the graduates leaving, the next group of new students starts March 10<sup>th</sup>. It’ll be nice to learn how to do facials with other new girls.  It will be weird to no longer be the newest group. I have a feeling that I may still be the youngest of the day classes.','Student\'s Story - After 3 weeks','','publish','open','open','','students-story-after-3-weeks','','','2014-03-03 18:33:08','2014-03-04 00:33:08','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1684',0,'post','',0),(1687,2,'2014-03-08 10:19:44','2014-03-08 16:19:44','<img src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/international-womens-day-march-8-ita.jpg\" class=\"size-full\" alt=\"Happy Women\'s Day!\" />\n\n<p>We wish each and every woman a happy International Women\'s Day! May your day - and life - be filled with success, joy, and beauty!</p>','Happy Women\'s Day!','','publish','open','open','','happy-womens-day','','','2014-03-08 10:19:44','2014-03-08 16:19:44','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1687',0,'post','',1),(1691,2,'2014-03-08 14:30:39','2014-03-08 20:30:39','<strong>Today is the <a href=\"http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/2014/03/08/happy-womens-day/\">International Women\'s Day</a>! So how fitting, that it is also the birth day of our president, Dr. Natalia Doran!</strong>\n\nWithout her, our Academy would not exist - but she is not just our founder, she is our leader, our engine for constant improvement, and our endless source for inspiration! Ten years ago she decided to revolutionize skin care education, and ever since she has worked tirelessly, changing hundreds of lives in the process.<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/happy-birthday-dr-doran.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1695\" alt=\"dr-doran-birthday-president\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/happy-birthday-dr-doran.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"288\" /></a>\n\n<strong>HAPPY BIRTHDAY, DR. PRESIDENT! We know that all that you have achieved so far is just a small drop of what is yet to come! We wish you happiness, health, and continued success!</strong>\n\n&nbsp;','Happy Birthday to Our President!!!','','publish','open','open','','happy-birthday-dr-president','','','2014-03-08 14:30:39','2014-03-08 20:30:39','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1691',0,'post','',0),(1692,2,'2014-03-08 14:16:26','2014-03-08 20:16:26','','Happy Birthday Dr. Doran','','inherit','open','open','','happy-birthday-dr-doran','','','2014-03-08 14:16:26','2014-03-08 20:16:26','',1691,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/happy-birthday-dr-doran.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1693,2,'2014-03-08 14:20:07','2014-03-08 20:20:07','Happy Birthday, Dr. Doran','Happy Birthday Dr. Doran','','inherit','open','open','','happy-birthday-dr-doran-2','','','2014-03-08 14:20:07','2014-03-08 20:20:07','',1691,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/happy-birthday-dr-doran1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1695,2,'2014-03-08 14:29:10','2014-03-08 20:29:10','happy birthday, Dr. Doran!','Happy Birthday Dr. Doran','','inherit','open','open','','happy-birthday-dr-doran-3','','','2014-03-08 14:29:10','2014-03-08 20:29:10','',1691,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/happy-birthday-dr-doran.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1697,2,'2014-03-10 13:25:07','2014-03-10 18:25:07','<strong>One of the most bittersweet parts of our job is saying \"GOODBYE\" to our graduating students!</strong>Of course, we are excited to see them all grown up and ready for the real world!  We have seen them work so hard, improving every day, every hour, and every minute of their training. Of course, we know that they are ready and that they will be successful beyond our wildest dreams! But our hearts break a little, knowing that we will not see them every day in class.\n\nLast week marked the last week of training for a large group of our esthetics students. Watching them say \"Goodbye\" to our school and each other was incredibly sweet (the room got so \"dusty\" that we had to shed a tear, or three... ;) ). Yet we know that they are ready for a new, life-long journey - and we can\'t wait to hear about their success.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_1699\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/last-day-photo2-copy.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1699 \" alt=\"last-Day-Aesthetics-Students\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/last-day-photo2-copy.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"306\" /></a> Some of the Esthetics students on their last day![/caption]\n\n<strong>One of the most exciting parts of our job is saying \"HELLO!\" to the new students!</strong>\n\nToday, students from three programs - and representing six countries! - are beginning their journey to success. We are very excited to welcome  phenomenal women to study <strong>Esthetics, Medical Assisting</strong>, and <strong>Esthetics Teaching</strong>! For two of the women, it\'s a homecoming - as they graduated from other programs before! We are honored that they have decided to join our family, and we look forward to every day with them!','Goodbye and Hello!','','publish','open','open','','goodbye-and-hello','','','2014-03-10 13:25:07','2014-03-10 18:25:07','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1697',0,'post','',0),(1698,2,'2014-03-10 13:14:06','2014-03-10 18:14:06','','last day photo2','','inherit','open','open','','last-day-photo2','','','2014-03-10 13:14:06','2014-03-10 18:14:06','',1697,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/last-day-photo2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1699,2,'2014-03-10 13:17:13','2014-03-10 18:17:13','','last day photo2 - Copy','','inherit','open','open','','last-day-photo2-copy','','','2014-03-10 13:17:13','2014-03-10 18:17:13','',1697,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/last-day-photo2-copy.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1704,2,'2014-03-11 16:30:52','2014-03-11 21:30:52','<div dir=\"ltr\">\n\n<strong>Here\'s another weekly blog post from our lovely Esthetics student, Alissa:</strong>\nA month ago yesterday was my first day of school.  Yesterday 3 other students joined the esthetician program, the medical assisting program started, and an alumni of the school has come back to become an esthetics teacher. One of the girls who have joined the esthetics program is my age! That was exciting to find out. I am still younger than her though. I have gotten good impressions off of all of the new people.\n\n<em><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">Fun fact</span>:</em> I had already met the alumna who started [the Esthetics Teacher program] at a spa where she works. She was the one who told me about ISBA! Last year, I knew I wanted to be an esthetician. I had never gotten anything done before, so I thought I should try getting waxed to know what it feels like. I went to get my underarms waxed, the first time it was not by her. There was still hair, it was not all too pleasant, and I was not completely satisfied. I went back again anyway, and that time she was my esthetician. It was a fantastic experience, she got everything, and it felt like nothing. She was also so nice, I told her that I wanted to be an esthetician and she told me about how wonderful this school was, so I checked it out. I am glad I decided to get my underarms waxed professionally; it would not have brought me to this school otherwise. Also, the quality of the education shines through that one receives here. I could not believe the difference in experience I had between her and the other girl at the same spa.\n\nMore to add to yesterday, we started from the beginning of rotation [after having studied makeup, business planning, and resume]! We went over chapters 1, 2, and 3. It was nice to come to the basics. Starting at the end of rotation was a bit strange, but not bad at all. To put very generally, we are now on the history of skincare, workplace common sense, and different opportunities for estheticians. Today we have learned how to set up the bed for a client, what products we use and why. I had set up a bed before, but it will be nice to understand the products we use and why. On Wednesday, Dr. Doran will have a presentation on medical aesthetics. Currently, I would like to go on the more medical side, so I am eager for tomorrow to arrive.\n\n</div>','First Month - A Student\'s Story','','publish','open','open','','first-month-a-students-story','','','2014-03-11 16:30:52','2014-03-11 21:30:52','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1704',0,'post','',0),(1714,2,'2014-03-21 12:23:39','2014-03-21 17:23:39','It is especially fitting that with the official beginning of spring, a season renowned for renewal, <b>International Skin Beauty Academy</b> has welcomed <b>Mr.</b> <b>Keith Ward, </b>an internationally celebrated makeup artist, to its family.<a href=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/keith-ward-family-isba.png\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1711\" alt=\"Keith-Ward-beauty-International-Skin-Beauty-Academy\" src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/keith-ward-family-isba.png\" width=\"500\" height=\"316\" /></a>\n\nMr. Ward said that he is “excited to be part of the faculty at International Skin Beauty Academy!” He added, “After more than twenty years of experience shaping the images of celebrities, entertainers, models, and other extraordinary people, I am ready to share my trade secrets!”\n\nAcademy’s president, Dr. Natalia Doran shared: “Our family is overjoyed to have someone of Mr. Keith’s caliber, both as an artist and a makeup artist! He will help us revolutionize the skin care industry even more!”\n\nMr. Ward will offer a multitude of classes and seminars, providing both advanced training to beauty professionals, and offering guidance to women who want to perfect their personal skills.\n\n<em><strong>To receive more information about the upcoming classes, please fill out the form information request below:</strong></em>\n\n[contact-form to=\'skinbeautyacademy@gmail.com\' subject=\'Makeup Courses\'][contact-field label=\'Name\' type=\'name\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Email\' type=\'email\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Website\' type=\'url\'/][contact-field label=\'Comment\' type=\'textarea\' required=\'1\'/][/contact-form]','Star Makeup Artist Joins Family','','publish','open','open','','star-makeup-artist-joins-ita','','','2014-03-21 12:23:39','2014-03-21 17:23:39','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1714',0,'post','',0),(1793,2,'2014-03-24 17:33:52','2014-03-24 22:33:52','<strong>We are excited to welcome to its family Ms. Julia Bowers, an internationally renowned permanent makeup artist.<a href=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/julia-bowers-international-training-academy-perm-makeup.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-1795\" src=\"http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/julia-bowers-international-training-academy-perm-makeup.jpg\" alt=\"permanent-makeup-artis-julia-bowers\" width=\"500\" height=\"397\" /></a></strong>\n<blockquote>“Being the best means extremely hard work and incredibly high standards”, said Academy’s president, Dr. Natalia Doran, “but we would not settle for anything else, and Ms. Julia shares our philosophy”.</blockquote>\nMs. Bowers is in-demand globally as one of the most skilled permanent makeup artists, as well as, one of the few who use the hand method. She brings with her almost three decades of unparalleled experience and skill, stating:\n<blockquote>“As a veteran in this field I feel it is important to pass this skill on to the next generation. We need to continue to service our clients/patients with the most knowledgeable and best educated technicians.”</blockquote>\nMs. Bowers lives in Massachusetts, where she is one of the few licensed technicians in the City of Boston who can legally perform permanent makeup/permanent cosmetics. In 2004 she created Pigmenta Permanent Cosmetics, to serve a wide range of clients. She is an elite educator, traveling internationally to train permanent makeup artists.\n\n<strong>The inaugural classes will take place over the course of four days, July 26 through July 29, 2014.</strong>\n\n<em><strong>To receive more information about the upcoming classes, please fill out the form information request below:</strong></em>\n\n[contact-form to=\'skinbeautyacademy@gmail.com\' subject=\'Permanent Makeup Classes\'][contact-field label=\'Name\' type=\'name\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Email\' type=\'email\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Telephone\' type=\'text\' required=\'1\'/][contact-field label=\'Comment\' type=\'textarea\' required=\'1\'/][/contact-form]','World-Class Permanent Makeup Artist Joins Team','','publish','open','open','','permanent-makeup-artist-joins-team','','','2014-03-24 17:33:52','2014-03-24 22:33:52','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=1793',0,'post','',0),(1795,2,'2014-03-24 17:32:53','2014-03-24 22:32:53','','Julia Bowers International Training Academy Perm Makeup','','inherit','open','open','','julia-bowers-international-training-academy-perm-makeup','','','2014-03-24 17:32:53','2014-03-24 22:32:53','',1793,'http://design-austin.com/ita/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/julia-bowers-international-training-academy-perm-makeup.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3130,2,'2014-04-03 12:13:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p><span style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\"> Two Wednesdays ago, Dr. Doran gave a medical esthetics presentation. There is no special licensing to be a medical, clinical, or paramedical esthetician.  But an esthetician can be trained in a medical setting to specialize in helping patients learn to care for changes in their skin.  Most states allow estheticians to treat only the stratum corneum, the top layer on the skin that consists mostly of dead skin cells. <span style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">An esthetician may not preform procedures, which fall within the spectrum of aesthetic medicine without physician\'s approval and supervision.</span> I can continue, but I don\'t want to spoil everything. All in all, I found the presentation to be very informative. <br /></span></p><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">        A couple weeks ago we went over the test for chapters 1,2, and 3. The norm for after taking a test is to highlight the next chapter, which is exactly what we did. We highlighted Chapter 4, which is all about sanitation. This was an intense chapter. I took AP Biology in high school, so some of the bacteria information was not new to me. Now pus, being defined as a fluid that is made up of  white blood cells, bacteria, dead skin cells, and some tissues... makes me look at acne differently. There were a lot of terms in that chapter, but I bet there are at least double in the next chapter, Anatomy.  </div><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">       However many Wednesdays ago, Dr. Doran gave a presentation on OSHA regulations. I like when Dr. Doran gives presentations; she explains things in an \"out of the box\" way that is very easy to pick up on. Chapter <span class=\"aBn\"><span class=\"aQJ\">4 may m</span></span>ake my stomach cringe at times, but hopefully that will be the last of that.</div><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">      Sanitation was definitely a chapter that worked well with me, I did not get a question wrong on the test. After grading that test last week Monday, we started Anatomy. That was a lot of highlighting, and is quite the bit of work. Thankfully Anatomy is a two-week chapter. Last week we got to practice more through a facial. We started putting enzyme therapy in the routine, and have moved to three massage moves on the chest. By the end of the week we also got to practice more of waxing. Starting out, it was very uncomfortable, most of us were having a bit of trouble. By the end of the class, we were not professionals, but we were much more comfortable. </div><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">      Monday marked week two of anatomy. There is quite a lot to know, but we do not have to know every little thing about the body. This is not medical school. What makes anatomy easier is translating all parts of the words. Anterior is front. Posterior is behind. Epi is above. Infa is inside. and so on. For example, auricularis anterior is a muscle in front of the ear. Something else that is big to know about anatomy is that cells are the basic unit. Cells with specific functions come together to make tissues. Tissues make up organs. Organs make up our body systems.</div><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">     Besides going over anatomy, we went of the lymphatic system. The lymphatic, or immune system, is commonly overlooked in western medicine. Lymph is the fluid of this system, and there is twice as much of lymph than blood in our body. There are 8-10 pints of blood in the body, so that is a lot of lymph. This system\'s integral parts are lymphatic vessels, lymph nodes, and lymphatic organs. This system only powered by movement and breathing. So those people who are sitting around at desks all day and remain inactive, it is not beneficial. After the presentation, we learned how to do a manual lymphatic drainage massage. It is very strange how fast it works. I am currently getting over a cold and suffering from allergies, and in the middle of the massage I could breathe. It was wonderful. </div><div style=\"font-family:arial, sans-serif;font-size:13px;\">     I am not sure what we will be doing tomorrow or the rest of the week, but it does not matter. It still feels nice to wake up and want to go to school.</div>','A student\'s story (continued)','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-04-03 12:13:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=3130',0,'post','',0),(4326,2,'2014-04-15 19:10:53','2014-04-16 00:10:53','<p>Today our most recent graduates have found our the State licensing exam results. Not only are they now all licensed estheticians, each one of them has ACED the exam, earning a near-perfect score. This is, of course, nothing new for our Academy. We have witnessed a generation after a generation of our graduates take on the challenge - and rise and exceed it. Yet, each time, we are incredibly proud of each woman!</p><p><span style=\"color:#073763;\">With the latest results in, we retain our position as the school with the highest scores, but, most importantly, we are still the school with the <b> <span style=\"color:#cc0000;\">MOST INTELLIGENT</span> </b>students!!!</span></p><p><a href=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/last-day-photo2-copy1.jpg\"><img id=\"i-4335\" class=\"size-full wp-image\" src=\"http://intlacademy.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/last-day-photo2-copy1.jpg?w=650\" alt=\"Image\" /></a></p>','Pride for the Next Generation','','publish','open','open','','pride-for-the-next-generation','','','2014-04-15 19:10:53','2014-04-16 00:10:53','',0,'http://intlacademy.wordpress.com/?p=4326',0,'post','',0),(4389,2,'2014-04-16 17:40:06','2014-04-16 22:40:06','<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#0a0a0a;background:white;\"> LEARN EVERYTHING YOU ALWAYS TO KNOW BUT WERE AFRAID TO ASK ABOUT MAKEUP! </span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#0a0a0a;background:white;\">A celebrity makeup artist, Keith Ward will offer a phenomenal makeup boot camp exclusively at ISBA and will share all of his wisdom!\n</span></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#0a0a0a;background:white;font-weight:normal;\">The class will cover: </span></strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Perfect makeup for all shapes</li>\n	<li>Applying perfect foundation</li>\n	<li>Creating great looks</li>\n	<li>Sanitation and Disinfection</li>\n	<li>Choosing the right brushes &amp; makeup</li>\n	<li>Demo and Practice</li>\n</ul>\n